  Additive Manufacturing (AM): Machines and Techniques
</div>
With the advent of faster and inexpensive controllers, additive manufacturing has become an incredibly accessible technology. These technologies and techniques, while futuristic, are very much a modern convenience available to everyone. <br> <br>

Additive Manufacturing refers to the process of creating something by strategically adding material where there once was none. The most common way of doing this is with a 3D printer which adds molten plastic together in layers to form a three dimensional object. 3D printing is in of itself a developing technology and has multiple different styles and processes that all fall under the larger umbrella of 3D printing. Below these different types are broken out and explained. <br> <br>

<button class="w3-button cm-button" onclick="expand('fdm')">Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM)</button>
<div id="fdm" class="w3-container w3-round-large cm-acordian w3-hide">
  Fused Deposition Modeling, more typically called FDM, is the process of converting a computer generated model into a physical object by depositing molten plastics layer by layer to form the final product. This is the most common form of 3D printing currently because of its simplicity and low cost. <br>
